Your developer is right. This is a Jackson version conflict — a classic transitive-vs-pinned mismatch, and the build logs prove it.

## Root cause

`READ_UNKNOWN_ENUM_VALUES_USING_DEFAULT_VALUE` was added to `JsonFormat.Feature` in **jackson-annotations 2.16**. Your runtime is loading an **older `jackson-annotations` (2.14.x)**, so `EnumDeserializer` (from a newer `jackson-databind`) calls a field that doesn't exist in the loaded annotations jar → `NoSuchFieldError`.

The build log shows exactly this skew. The Spring Boot plugin's own classpath pulled in 2.14.2:

```
jackson-annotations-2.14.2.jar
jackson-databind-2.14.2.jar
```

…while your application dependencies resolve a mix:
- `jackson-databind` → **2.17.2** (Spring Boot 3.3.3 BOM)
- `jackson-datatype-joda` → **2.17.2**
- but you also have explicit pins fighting the BOM:

```gradle
implementation 'com.fasterxml.jackson.datatype:jackson-datatype-joda:2.12.3'   // ← drags 2.12
implementation group: 'com.fasterxml.jackson.core', name: 'jackson-databind', version: '2.17.2'
implementation 'com.fasterxml.jackson.core:jackson-databind:2.15.2'            // ← drags 2.15
```

And the build log confirms the old annotations jar is physically present and resolved:

```
jackson-datatype-joda-2.12.3.pom
jackson-databind-2.15.2.pom
jackson-bom-2.12.3.pom
jackson-annotations-2.14.2.jar   ← this is what's on the runtime classpath
```

Your **fat jar (122M bootJar) ends up with `jackson-annotations` resolved low** (2.14 from the buildpack/transitive path) while `databind` is 2.17 — incompatible by Jackson's own rule that all `jackson-*` modules must share one version line.

## The fix

Remove every hardcoded Jackson version and let the Spring Boot 3.3.3 BOM govern all of them (it aligns the whole stack at 2.17.2). In `build.gradle`, delete these lines:

```gradle
implementation 'com.fasterxml.jackson.datatype:jackson-datatype-joda:2.12.3'
implementation group: 'com.fasterxml.jackson.core', name: 'jackson-databind', version: '2.17.2'
implementation 'com.fasterxml.jackson.core:jackson-databind:2.15.2'
```

Replace with unversioned (BOM-managed) declarations:

```gradle
implementation 'com.fasterxml.jackson.datatype:jackson-datatype-joda'
implementation 'com.fasterxml.jackson.core:jackson-databind'
```

(`databind` is already transitive via `spring-boot-starter-web`/`json`, so you may not need to declare it at all.)

To guarantee alignment and prevent any stray transitive from clawing back, add a platform constraint:

```gradle
dependencies {
    implementation platform('com.fasterxml.jackson:jackson-bom:2.17.2')
    ...
}
```

## Verify before rebuilding

Run this in the repo to confirm there's exactly one Jackson line:

```bash
./gradlew dependencyInsight --dependency jackson-annotations --configuration runtimeClasspath
./gradlew dependencyInsight --dependency jackson-databind     --configuration runtimeClasspath
```

Both should report **2.17.2**. Then check the actual fat jar (this is the real proof, since `bootJar` is what runs in the pod):

```bash
unzip -l build/libs/epay_payment_service-dev-*.jar | grep -i jackson
```

You should see a single version across `jackson-core`, `jackson-databind`, `jackson-annotations`, and all `jackson-datatype-*` / `jackson-module-*`. If `jackson-annotations` shows 2.14 there, the runtime will still break.

## Two side notes from the logs

- `gradle.properties` declares `jackson_joda=2.12.3` and `jackson_databind=2.15.2`, but `build.gradle` doesn't consistently reference those vars — it hardcodes versions inline. Once you switch to BOM management, drop those two properties to avoid future confusion.
- The crash-loop (`4 restarts`) is purely this `NoSuchFieldError` thrown at deserialization of the initiate/qr-sign payloads, surfacing as the generic `handleGenericException`. It's not the scheduler-starvation issue from before — different failure mode. Fixing the Jackson alignment should clear both the crash-loop and the UI payment error.

The dependencies are **not** resolving cleanly — the inline pins are the conflict. BOM alignment is the fix.
